"1452":"1452","after 1471":"na 1471","1516":"1516","1416":"1416","1504":"1504","1537":"1537","Nynäs Sätesgård, Åby, Kalmar, Kalmar (H) län, Sweden":"Åby, Kalmar, Zweden","Länsi-Suomi, Finland":"Länsi-Suomi, Finland","Honungaby, Vallby, Uppland, Sverige":"Vallby, Tibble, Uppsala, Zweden","Simtuna, Vallby, Uppland, Sverige":"Simtuna, Uppsala, Zweden"},"en":{"1416–1516":"1416–1516","1440–1537":"1440–1537","1442–Male":"1442–Deceased","1453–1516":"1453–1516","1454–1504":"1454–1504","1401–1452":"1401–1452","1416–1445":"1416–1445","–1471":"–1471","–1462":"–1462","before 1462":"before 1462","29. oktober 1416":"29 October 1416","1495":"1495","1462":"1462","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1471":"1471","1436":"1436","1445":"1445","1401":"1401","1454":"1454","1497":"1497","1453":"1453","1442":"1442","29 oct 1445":"29 October 1445","1452":"1452","after 1471":"after 1471","1516":"1516","1416":"1416","1504":"1504","1537":"1537","Nynäs Sätesgård, Åby, Kalmar, Kalmar (H) län, Sweden":"Åby, Kalmar, Sweden","Länsi-Suomi, Finland":"Länsi-Suomi, Finland","Honungaby, Vallby, Uppland, Sverige":"Vallby, Tibble, Uppsala, Sweden","Simtuna, Vallby, Uppland, Sverige":"Simtuna, Uppsala, Sweden","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ulv","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German:","habitational name from the city of this name in Baden-Württemberg. The placename is from the root <i>uel</i>, an unattested word meaning ‘turn, wind, roll’, or from <i>el-</i> or <i>ol-</i> ‘flow’, a reference in either case to the influx of the Blan river into the Danube.","from a short form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Odolmar</i> (see   Ulmer   2). Compare   Ollom  ,   Ullom  ,   Ullum  ,   Wollam  , and   Woolam  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wollam","meanings":["English (Shropshire and Lancashire): variant of the Devon surname <b>Woolland</b>, perhaps a habitational name from Woolland in Dorset, named from Old English <i>wynne</i> ‘pasture, meadow’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’. Alternatively, but less likely, a topographic name from Middle English <i>wough</i> ‘bent, crooked’ + <i>land(e)</i>, <i>lond(e)</i> ‘land’ (Old English <i>wōh</i> + <i>land</i>), perhaps denoting a person who lived at or near a bend in a stream or river, or for someone from any place so named, such as Wollensbrook in Great Amwell (Hertfordshire). This surname is rare in Britain.","Americanized form of German   Ulm  ."]},{"name":"Ulmer","meanings":["German:","habitational name for someone from the city of Ulm (see   Ulm   1).","from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Odolmar</i>, composed of the elements <i>odal</i> ‘inherited property’ + <i>mār</i> ‘famous’."]},{"name":"Ullom","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Ulm  ."]},{"name":"Ollom","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Ulm  ."]},{"name":"Ullum","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Ulm  ."]}]},{"name":"Ingeborg","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old Norse personal name from the name of the fertility god <i>Ing</i> + <i>borg</i> ‘fortification’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1702076,"age":20,"year":"1436","julianDay":2245548,"title":"The Engelbrekt Rebellion","description":"Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson, a Swedish mine owner and statesman, led a rebellion against Eric of Pomerania, King of the Kalmar Union. Sweden was upset with the Danes' interference with Swedish exports and unjust collection of taxes. The Engelbrekt Rebellion led to the deposing of Eric of Pomerania and the eventual dissolution of the Kalmar Union.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1357051,"age":79,"year":"1495","julianDay":2267098,"description":"Russians forces invade Sweden.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702078,"age":79,"year":"1495","toYear":"1497","julianDay":2267098,"title":"The Russo-Swedish War","description":"While in an alliance with Grand Prince Ivan III of Moscow, King Hans of Denmark and Nor